---
export const prerender = true;
import BlogLayout from '../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
---

<BlogLayout
  title="Board Openness Control in Scrabble — Open vs Closed Board Strategy"
  description="Learn when to open the board for high scoring and when to close it down defensively. Board control tactics used by tournament players to dictate the flow of the game."
  keywords="board control scrabble, open board strategy, closed board scrabble, defensive scrabble, board openness, scrabble board management, controlling the board"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Board Openness Control in Scrabble — Open vs Closed Board Strategy",
    "description": "Learn when to open the board for high scoring and when to close it down defensively. Board control tactics used by tournament players to dictate the flow of the game.",
    "datePublished": "2026-06-15",
    "author": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com", "url": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com" },
    "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com" },
    "mainEntityOfPage": { "@type": "WebPage", "@id": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com/blog/board-openness-control" }
  })} />

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What does open vs closed board mean in Scrabble?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "An open board has multiple available lanes leading to premium squares, hookable word endings, and space for long words or bingos. A closed board has few scoring opportunities — premium squares are blocked, words are tightly packed, and extensions are difficult. Players intentionally open or close the board depending on their position and tile strength." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "When should you open the board in Scrabble?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Open the board when you're behind and need big plays to catch up, when you have a strong rack with bingo potential or high-value tiles near premium squares, or when your opponent is playing defensively and you need to create opportunities they can't all block." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How do tournament players control board openness?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Tournament players control openness by choosing where to play — tight spots close the board, extensions toward premium squares open it. They use dead-end letters (V, W, C) to limit hooks, play short words perpendicular to threat lanes for blocks, and deliberately create or deny bingo lanes depending on whether they're ahead or behind." }
      }
    ]
  })} />

  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <article class="prose prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose flex items-center gap-1">
        <a href="/blog/" class="hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">← Blog</a>
        <span class="mx-1">›</span>
        <a href="/blog/strategy/" class="hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors text-gray-300">Strategy</a>
      </nav>

      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Board Openness Control in Scrabble — Open vs Closed Board Strategy</h1>

      <div class="not-prose mb-8 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-gray-400">
        <time datetime="2026-06-15">June 15, 2026</time>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
        <span>6 min read</span>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
        <a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🔤</span> Word Finder</a>
      </div>

      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-300 mb-8">
        Every Scrabble board tells a story — open boards invite explosive scoring and bingos, while closed boards grind opponents into low-point exchanges. The difference between a casual player and a tournament competitor often comes down to one skill: knowing when to open the board and when to shut it down. Master board openness control and you dictate the pace of every game you play.
      </p>

      <!-- Hero Card -->
      <div class="not-prose my-8 p-6 rounded-2xl border-2 border-amber-500/50 bg-gradient-to-r from-amber-950/30 to-yellow-950/20 relative overflow-hidden">
        <div class="absolute top-3 right-4 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-amber-500/70">👑 Golden Rule</div>
        <p class="text-2xl font-black text-white tracking-wider mb-2">CONTROL THE BOARD = CONTROL THE GAME</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-300 font-semibold mb-3">The player who decides whether the board stays open or closed holds the strategic advantage</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">Board openness isn't something that just happens — it's a deliberate choice. Every word you place either opens new scoring lanes or seals them shut. Make that choice consciously.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">What Open and Closed Boards Mean</h2>

      <p>Board openness describes how many scoring opportunities exist at any point in the game. It's not binary — boards exist on a spectrum from completely locked down to wide open with multiple premium square lanes available.</p>

      <!-- Comparison Cards: Open vs Closed -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🟢 Open Board</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Multiple lanes to TWS/DWS squares. Hookable word endings (E, S, D, R) exposed. Space for 7-letter bingos. Words extend in multiple directions. Average turn scores: <span class="text-white font-medium">28-40 pts</span>.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/30 bg-red-950/10">
          <p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🔴 Closed Board</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Premium squares blocked or unreachable. Dead-end letters (V, W, C) at word endings. No bingo lanes available. Plays limited to 3-4 letter words. Average turn scores: <span class="text-white font-medium">12-20 pts</span>.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Stat Strip -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">28-40</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Avg pts/turn (open board)</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">12-20</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Avg pts/turn (closed board)</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">2×</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Bingo frequency on open boards</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>Understanding this spectrum is the first step. An open board benefits the player with better tiles, stronger vocabulary, or a trailing position. A closed board benefits the player who's ahead and wants to protect their lead by limiting comeback potential.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">When to Open the Board</h2>

      <p>Opening the board means creating new scoring lanes — extending words toward premium squares, leaving hookable endings exposed, and building in directions that allow long plays. You actively want an open board in specific situations.</p>

      <!-- Card Grid: When to Open -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">📉 You're Behind</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Trailing by 30+ points? You need big plays to catch up. Closed boards make comebacks nearly impossible — open it up and give yourself shots at 40+ point turns.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🎯 Strong Rack</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Holding a blank, S tiles, or bingo-ready letters (like RETAINS)? An open board lets you deploy them for maximum value. Don't waste premium tiles on a locked-down position.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🧩 Need Bingo Lanes</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Bingos require 7+ consecutive open squares. If no bingo lane exists on a closed board, create one — even if your opponent might also use it.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🔄 Opponent Plays Tight</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">If your opponent is defensive by nature, they'll struggle to exploit open lanes. Force the board open and play your game — they'll feel uncomfortable in open positions.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Insight Callout -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 The "I'm Behind" Rule</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">When trailing by <span class="text-white font-medium">40+ points</span>, always prefer the play that opens lanes — even if it scores slightly less. A closed board when you're behind is a slow death. You need volatility to come back, and open boards create volatility.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">When to Close the Board</h2>

      <p>Closing the board is the defensive counterpart — you're restricting scoring opportunities for both players. This is strategically correct when maintaining a lead matters more than scoring a few extra points.</p>

      <!-- Purple Strategy Tiles: When to Close -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Leading late game:</span> With 20 or fewer tiles in the bag, a 40+ point lead is nearly unassailable on a closed board. Your opponent simply doesn't have enough turns to catch up with 12-point plays.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Opponent holds a blank:</span> If you suspect your opponent has a blank tile (or you know from tile tracking), close the board to deny them bingo lanes. A blank without a lane to play it is worthless.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">You have weak tiles:</span> Holding UUIIO? A closed board keeps scores low for everyone. You sacrifice less when the entire game is low-scoring. Wait for better draws while limiting damage.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Opponent is a bingo machine:</span> Against players who consistently find 7-letter plays, deny them the lanes they need. Force them into 3-4 tile plays where their vocabulary advantage matters less.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">How to Open and Close Practically</h2>

      <p>Board control isn't abstract — it's specific moves you can make right now. Here's how to physically open or close a board with your tile placement.</p>

      <!-- Numbered Steps: How to Close -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-purple-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">🔒 How to Close a Board</p>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">1</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Play in <span class="text-white font-medium">crowded areas</span> — place tiles adjacent to existing words rather than extending into empty board space.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">2</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">End words with <span class="text-white font-medium">dead-end letters</span> (V, W, C) — these have very few valid extensions, preventing hooks.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">3</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Play <span class="text-white font-medium">perpendicular blocks</span> — short words that cut across lanes leading to premium squares.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">4</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Avoid creating <span class="text-white font-medium">parallel opportunities</span> — don't place words that leave clean parallel lanes for opponents.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">5</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Use tiles that <span class="text-white font-medium">consume space without creating openings</span> — short plays touching multiple existing words.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Card Grid: Opening Techniques -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-cyan-500/30 bg-cyan-950/10">
          <p class="text-cyan-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🔓 Extend toward premium</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Play words that reach within 1-2 squares of TWS/DWS. This creates a scoring lane you (or your opponent) can exploit next turn.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-cyan-500/30 bg-cyan-950/10">
          <p class="text-cyan-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🔓 Leave hookable endings</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">End words with E, S, D, R, or Y — letters that invite extensions. GAME can become GAMED, GAMES, GAMER, GAMY.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-cyan-500/30 bg-cyan-950/10">
          <p class="text-cyan-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🔓 Create bingo lanes</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Open a row or column with 7+ consecutive empty squares connected to existing tiles. This invites full-rack plays for 50-point bonuses.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-cyan-500/30 bg-cyan-950/10">
          <p class="text-cyan-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🔓 Play into empty quadrants</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Extend the board into unused corners. Fresh premium squares become available, and new parallel opportunities appear.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Dig Deeper -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-indigo-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">📚 Dig Deeper</p>
        <div class="grid gap-2">
          <a href="/blog/defensive-scrabble-strategy/" class="flex items-center gap-2 p-2 rounded-lg hover:bg-indigo-900/20 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-indigo-400 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform shrink-0">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-indigo-300 transition-colors">Defensive Scrabble Strategy — blocking techniques and when defense costs too much</span>
          </a>
          <a href="/blog/offensive-scrabble-strategy/" class="flex items-center gap-2 p-2 rounded-lg hover:bg-indigo-900/20 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-indigo-400 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform shrink-0">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-indigo-300 transition-colors">Offensive Scrabble Strategy — opening lanes and maximizing every turn</span>
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Reading Your Opponent's Intent</h2>

      <p>Board control is a two-player chess match. Your opponent's moves reveal whether they want an open or closed board — and understanding their intent lets you counter it.</p>

      <!-- Purple Strategy Tiles: Signals -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">They're exchanging tiles:</span> An opponent who swaps tiles is often building toward a bingo. They want an open board. Start closing lanes preemptively — deny them the space to deploy their 7-letter word.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">They're playing short, tight words:</span> This signals defensive intent — they're closing the board. If you need an open game, counteract by extending into empty quadrants and creating new lanes they haven't blocked.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">They placed a hookable ending near a TWS:</span> They're either setting up their next turn or baiting you into a trap. Check if using that hook exposes something worse for you. Sometimes the "obvious" play is a defensive sacrifice.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">They scored low on a crowded play:</span> Accepting a low score to play in a congested area is a strong signal they're closing intentionally. They're choosing position over points — respect that and adjust your strategy accordingly.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Insight Callout -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-cyan-500/30 bg-cyan-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-cyan-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">🧠 Counter-Strategy</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">When your opponent wants the board <span class="text-white font-medium">closed</span>, open it. When they want it <span class="text-white font-medium">open</span>, close it. The player who dictates board state forces their opponent to play reactively rather than executing their own plan.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Putting It All Together</h2>

      <p>Board openness control is situational — there's no single correct answer. The right choice depends on your score, your tiles, your opponent's tendencies, and the game phase. Here's the decision framework tournament players use every turn.</p>

      <!-- Decision Framework Table -->
      <div class="overflow-x-auto not-prose my-6">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border border-gray-700 rounded-lg overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
          <thead class="bg-gray-800">
            <tr>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Situation</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Board Action</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Why</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-800">
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">Leading by 50+, late game</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-red-400 font-medium">Close</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Protect the lead — deny comeback plays</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">Trailing by 30+</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400 font-medium">Open</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Need volatility — big plays require space</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">Holding a blank + bingo rack</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400 font-medium">Open</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Need a 7-tile lane to deploy bingo</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">Opponent has blank (you tracked)</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-red-400 font-medium">Close</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Deny bingo lanes — blank without space is dead</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">Weak rack (UUIIO)</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-red-400 font-medium">Close</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Low scores hurt less when both score low</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">Even score, strong tiles</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400 font-medium">Open</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Press the advantage — deploy strength aggressively</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- Final Insight -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-amber-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">🏆 Tournament Mindset</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">Ask yourself before every play: <span class="text-white font-medium">"Do I want this board more open or more closed after my turn?"</span> Then choose the placement that moves the board in that direction — even if it costs 3-5 points compared to a "neutral" alternative.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Related Articles Aside -->
      <aside class="border-t border-gray-800 mt-12 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Related Articles</h3>
        <div class="grid gap-3">
          <a href="/blog/blocking-triple-word-squares/" class="flex items-center gap-3 p-3 rounded-lg border border-gray-800 hover:border-blue-700 hover:bg-blue-900/10 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-blue-500 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">Blocking Triple Word Squares — Denying Premium Positions</span>
          </a>
          <a href="/blog/hotspots-and-dead-zones/" class="flex items-center gap-3 p-3 rounded-lg border border-gray-800 hover:border-blue-700 hover:bg-blue-900/10 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-blue-500 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">Hotspots and Dead Zones — Where Points Live on the Board</span>
          </a>
          <a href="/blog/playing-scrabble-with-a-lead/" class="flex items-center gap-3 p-3 rounded-lg border border-gray-800 hover:border-blue-700 hover:bg-blue-900/10 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-blue-500 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">Playing Scrabble With a Lead — Protecting Your Advantage</span>
          </a>
        </div>
      </aside>

      <!-- CTA -->
      <div class="not-prose mt-10 p-5 bg-gradient-to-r from-blue-900/20 to-blue-800/20 border border-blue-800 rounded-xl">
        <div class="flex items-center justify-between gap-4 flex-wrap">
          <p class="text-sm text-blue-300 font-medium">🔤 Find your highest-scoring words — free, instant, no signup needed</p>
          <a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg bg-blue-500 hover:bg-blue-400 text-gray-950 text-sm font-semibold transition-colors">Open Word Finder →</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose mt-8 text-center">
        <a href="/blog/" class="text-sm text-gray-400 hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">← Back to all articles</a>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</BlogLayout>
